**Database Optimization Complete** ✅

**Problem:** The `orders` table (500M rows) had only a primary key index on `id`. Every query filtering or sorting by `user_id`, `order_date`, or `status` was doing a full sequential scan — brutal on a half-billion row table.

**Indexes created (all `CONCURRENTLY`):**

| Index | Column | Why |
|---|---|---|
| `idx_orders_user_id` | `user_id` | "Show me all orders for this user" — the most common query pattern |
| `idx_orders_order_date` | `order_date` | Range queries, date filtering, chronological sorting |
| `idx_orders_status` | `status` | Filtering by order status (pending, shipped, etc.) |

**Safety:** All three were built with `CREATE INDEX CONCURRENTLY`, which only takes a brief `ShareUpdateExclusiveLock` at start and end — INSERT/UPDATE/DELETE operations continued uninterrupted throughout. No locks remain on the table.

Users should notice a significant improvement in order-related query performance.
